ntology that affirms the basic principle of human asymmetrical dependence on more-than-human nature. Integrating environmental ethics with the latest work in political ecology, Peterson argues it is important to understand that the world is not made for us, and that coming to terms with this fact is a condition for survival in future human and more-than-human communities of liberation and solidarity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEnvironmental ethics. 0aEnvironmentalismxPhilosophy. 0aHuman ecology. 0aNaturexEffect of human beings on. 0aPhilosophy of nature. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Ecology. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2020z978311149149340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847961340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438479613423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438479613/original  a978-3-11-149149-3  SUNY Press eBook Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles